<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="253" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[136,1452,158,868]" pageId="6" pageNumber="253">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,353,410,436]" pageId="6" pageNumber="253">Discussion:—</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[353,653,410,436]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Crassulaceae" genus="Echeveria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Saxifragales" pageId="6" pageNumber="253" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cerrograndensis">
<emphasis box="[353,653,410,436]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="253">Echeveria cerrograndensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs to series Gibbiflorae (Baker)A. 
<bibRefCitation author="Berger, A." box="[1087,1302,410,436]" pageId="6" pageNumber="253" pagination="352 - 483" refId="ref2906" refString="Berger, A. (1930) Crassulaceae. In: A. Engler &amp; K. Prantl (eds.), Die naturlichen Pflanzenfamilien 18 A (2 nd ed.). W. Engelmann, Leipzig, pp. 352 - 483." type="book chapter" year="1930">Berger (1930: 474)</bibRefCitation>
, sensu 
<bibRefCitation author="Moran, R." pageId="6" pageNumber="253" pagination="184 - 186" refId="ref3389" refString="Moran, R. (1974) Division of genus Echeveria into series. In: Jacobsen, H. (ed.), Lexicon on succulent plants. Blandford Prees, London, pp. 184 - 186." type="book chapter" year="1974">Moran (1974)</bibRefCitation>
, a group consisting of medium to large size stemmed plants, lacking pubescence, with a cimose paniculated inflorescence with cincinate lateral branches (
<bibRefCitation author="Uhl, C. H." box="[674,789,482,508]" pageId="6" pageNumber="253" pagination="121 - 145" refId="ref3591" refString="Uhl, C. H. (2002) Chromosomes and hybrids of Echeveria (Crassulaceae). VII. Series Gibbiflorae (Baker) Berger. Haseltonia 9: 121 - 145. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.2985 / 1070 - 0048 (2005) 11 [138: cahoed] 2.0. co; 2" type="journal article" year="2002">Uhl 2002</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Kimnach, M." box="[806,979,482,508]" pageId="6" pageNumber="253" pagination="103 - 128" refId="ref3293" refString="Kimnach, M. (2003) Echeveria. In: Eggli, U. (ed.), Illustrated Handbook of Succulent Plants: Crassulaceae. Springer, Berlin, pp. 103 - 128." type="book chapter" year="2003">Kimnach 2003</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Meyran-Garcia, J. &amp; Lopez-Chavez, L." box="[996,1447,482,508]" pageId="6" pageNumber="253" refId="ref3353" refString="Meyran-Garcia, J. &amp; Lopez-Chavez, L. (2003) Las Crasulaceas de Mexico. Sociedad Mexicana de Cactologia, A. C. Mexico, D. F., 234 pp." type="book" year="2003">Meyrán-García &amp; López-Chávez 2003</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Carrillo-Reyes, P. &amp; Sosa, V. &amp; Mort, M. E." box="[136,436,518,544]" pageId="6" pageNumber="253" pagination="267 - 276" refId="ref3028" refString="Carrillo-Reyes, P., Sosa, V. &amp; Mort, M. E. (2009) Molecular phylogeny of the Acre clade (Crassulaceae): Dealing with the lack of definitions for Echeveria and Sedum. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 53: 267 - 276. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1016 / j. ympev. 2009.05.022" type="journal article" year="2009">
Carrillo-Reyes 
<emphasis box="[309,367,518,544]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="253">et al.</emphasis>
2009
</bibRefCitation>
). However, 
<taxonomicName box="[573,788,518,544]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Crassulaceae" genus="Echeveria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Saxifragales" pageId="6" pageNumber="253" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cerrograndensis">
<emphasis box="[573,788,518,544]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="253">E. cerrograndensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a rather small plant. The caulescent habit with cymosepaniculate inflorescence and lateral cincinate branches suggested a close morphological relationship to 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="253">
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Crassulaceae" genus="Echeveria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Saxifragales" pageId="6" pageNumber="253" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="fulgens">Echeveria fulgens</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
of series Gibbiflorae (
<bibRefCitation author="Moran, R." box="[473,616,590,616]" pageId="6" pageNumber="253" pagination="184 - 186" refId="ref3389" refString="Moran, R. (1974) Division of genus Echeveria into series. In: Jacobsen, H. (ed.), Lexicon on succulent plants. Blandford Prees, London, pp. 184 - 186." type="book chapter" year="1974">Moran 1974</bibRefCitation>
), actually a complex that might contain several species (
<bibRefCitation author="Uhl, C. H." box="[1240,1349,590,616]" pageId="6" pageNumber="253" pagination="121 - 145" refId="ref3591" refString="Uhl, C. H. (2002) Chromosomes and hybrids of Echeveria (Crassulaceae). VII. Series Gibbiflorae (Baker) Berger. Haseltonia 9: 121 - 145. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.2985 / 1070 - 0048 (2005) 11 [138: cahoed] 2.0. co; 2" type="journal article" year="2002">Uhl 2002</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Pilbeam, J." pageId="6" pageNumber="253" refId="ref3430" refString="Pilbeam, J. (2008) The genus Echeveria. The British Cactus &amp; Succulent Society, Essex, 333 pp." type="book" year="2008">Pilbeam 2008</bibRefCitation>
). A close examination of the flowers allowed us to conclude that we were dealing with an undescribed taxon here described as a new species. 
<taxonomicName box="[449,753,662,688]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Crassulaceae" genus="Echeveria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Saxifragales" pageId="6" pageNumber="253" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cerrograndensis">
<emphasis box="[449,753,662,688]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="253">Echeveria cerrograndensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also morphologically close to 
<taxonomicName box="[1123,1263,662,688]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Crassulaceae" genus="Echeveria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Saxifragales" pageId="6" pageNumber="253" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="roseiflora">
<emphasis box="[1123,1263,662,688]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="253">E. roseiflora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sharing with the latter the non bicolored corolla, red thecae, red nectaries and length of pedicels. However, it differs from the latter in having shorter leaves 3–6 vs. 
<quantity box="[477,579,734,761]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" metricValueMax="10.0" metricValueMin="6.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="253" unit="cm" value="8.0" valueMax="10.0" valueMin="6.0">6–10 cm</quantity>
; broadly obovate vs. oblanceolate-spatulate, leaf margin straight and pinkish vs. crenulated and reddish; shorter inflorescence 11–22(–35) vs. 
<quantity box="[872,987,770,797]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.2" metricValueMax="5.4" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="253" unit="cm" value="52.0" valueMax="54.0" valueMin="50.0">50–54 cm</quantity>
; smaller total number of flowers 4–11 vs. 18–20; shorter corolla 11–12 vs. 
<quantity box="[505,619,806,833]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" metricValueMax="1.6" metricValueMin="1.4" pageId="6" pageNumber="253" unit="cm" value="15.0" valueMax="16.0" valueMin="14.0">14–16 cm</quantity>
, pedicels straight vs. recurved (
<tableCitation box="[971,1055,806,832]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="6.[136,224,916,940]" captionText="TABLE 1. Differences between Echeveria cerrograndensis, E. fulgens and E. roseiflora." pageId="6" pageNumber="253">Table 1</tableCitation>
). The following key can be used to determine the species of the 
<taxonomicName box="[456,657,842,868]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Crassulaceae" genus="Echeveria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Saxifragales" pageId="6" pageNumber="253" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="fulgens">
<emphasis box="[456,657,842,868]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="253">Echeveria fulgens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
complex.
</paragraph>
